Is it true that: \begin{equation*}
\int_0^af(x)dx=\int_0^af(a-x)dx?
\end{equation*} Because I know that: \begin{equation*}
\int_0^af(x)\,dx=F(a)-F(0)~\text{and}~\int_0^af(a-x)\,dx=F(a-a)-F(a-0)=F(0)-F(a)
\end{equation*} So I got: $F(a)-F(0)=F(0)-F(a)$ and that's not necessarily true.

Anyone who has taken a course in linear algebra knows how to prove the eigenvalues of a self-adjoint operator are real or the eigenvalues of a skew-self-adjoint operator are purely imaginary. This is easily extended to the spectrum of differential operators on Hilbert spaces. Conversely, how does one go about proving that a differential operator has no purely imaginary eigenvalues? Indeed, what condition can be imposed on a first order differential operator $L$: 
\begin{equation*}
Lu =A \frac{du}{dt} + Bu
\end{equation*}
for $u: S^1 \to \mathbb{R}^n$ that ensures the spectrum of $L$ contains no purely imaginary eigenvalues? If $n=2m$ and
\begin{equation*}
A= \left( \begin{array}{cc}
0 & -I  \\
I & 0  \end{array} \right)
\end{equation*} then the first order part of $L$ is self-adjoint, so what condition can be imposed on $B$ so that the eigenvalues are not imaginary?
